Here are the findings for the getRequests endpoint in ConsumerController.java.

Endpoint path
- Full HTTP request path: /consumer/requests
- Path parameters: none (no {id} or similar placeholders)

HTTP methods supported by the code for this endpoint
- All methods acceptable: No. The method is explicitly mapped only to GET.
- GET: Yes. getRequests is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/requests", method = RequestMethod.GET).
- HEAD: Yes (based on framework behavior). Although not explicitly declared, Spring MVC will handle HEAD requests for existing GET mappings by default.
- OPTIONS: Yes (based on framework behavior). Spring MVC will respond to OPTIONS for mapped endpoints, typically with an Allow header indicating supported methods.
- POST: No. No mapping for POST on /consumer/requests.
- PUT: No. No mapping for PUT on /consumer/requests.
- DELETE: No. No mapping for DELETE on /consumer/requests.
- PATCH: No. No mapping for PATCH on /consumer/requests.
- TRACE: No. No mapping for TRACE on /consumer/requests.

Explanation
- The getRequests endpoint is defined with a GET mapping at /consumer/requests and is secured to ROLE_USER. There is no annotation for other HTTP verbs on this method, so only GET is explicitly supported by the code.
- HEAD and OPTIONS are not explicitly defined but are typically handled by Spring MVC for existing mappings:
  - HEAD requests for a GET-mapped endpoint are usually served by the same method, with a header-only response.
  - OPTIONS requests are usually answered by the framework with an appropriate Allow header listing the supported methods for that path.
- All other methods (POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, TRACE) are not implemented for this endpoint in the provided code.

In summary:
- Path: /consumer/requests
- GET: Acceptable
- HEAD: Acceptable (framework-handled for GET mappings)
- OPTIONS: Acceptable (framework-handled)
- POST/PUT/DELETE/PATCH/TRACE: Not acceptable (not implemented in code)
